Dear all,

The decision to hold the PoCG conference in St Petersburg this year was
made by the PoCG steering committee. The intention was to reach out to the
group of game scholars working at St Petersburg State University who have
made a notable contribution to the community, particularly at the PoCG 2018
conference, and to accept their bid as hosts. I was not involved in this
decision but I have confidence that the committee thought about the issues
currently being discussed. I believe that where the conference series has
previously been held was taken into account; St Petersburg will mark the
farthest afield from Western Europe that the series has gone, with perhaps
the exception of Istanbul in 2014. That is to say, there was the intention
to be less Western-centric and to be inclusive of scholars who might
otherwise not have been able to participate, building bridges between
academic communities. As has already been mentioned, some of those who
might be excluded by the decision to only hold academic conferences in
democratic countries include LGBT+ scholars from non-democratic countries.

There obviously has to be a balancing exercise as to who is included and
who else are then excluded by this very act of inclusion. Further, who is
making the decision and how they are doing so must also be scrutinised. I
believe that we are interrogating this now on Gamesnetwork. As a result, it
is appropriate for the steering committee to review the situation and to
consider what can be done to foster inclusivity. They will report back
soon. I will also consult again with the organising committee.

This conference will not be deemed by the Russian government to be
LGBT-themed. We very much welcome any LGBT+ content that is germane to the
conference theme of =E2=80=98the aesthetics of computer games=E2=80=99 and =
I do not believe
that the inclusion of such content will lead to attention from government
forces, particularly because there will not be anyone present under the age
of 18 and also because it is a small-scale English-speaking conference. We
are now, however, considering having all the workshops and panels be on the
theme of =E2=80=98diversity in games=E2=80=99, with the papers still being =
on =E2=80=98the
aesthetics of computer games=E2=80=99. More details on this will follow.

It goes without saying that no city is safe. London, where I live, is
deemed a 'safe' city, but has recently seen homophobic hate crimes rise.
https://www.met.police.uk/sd/stats-and-data/met/hate-crime-dashboard/

A particularly nasty attack on a bus against two women was just reported
last week. Of course London does not lie in an authoritarian state.
Traveling to another city in another country involves a calculated risk for
those of us who are LGBT+. It is a highly personal decision to be made
after some thought and on the basis of the available information. Here, it
may be appropriate to distinguish between safety in Russia taken as a whole
(listed as a lowly 157 in the 2018 Spartacus Guide), and safety in St
Petersburg, perhaps its most LGBT-friendly city. On the one hand, it may
have been paternalistic for us to point to particular scattered sources
that one should consult when making this personal decision, but on the
other, we could perhaps have done more to provide guidance. How to provide
this guidance - over and above having encouraged individuals to contact us
- will be considered by the steering committee.

The technical feasibility of teleconferencing has not been settled and is
still on the discussion agenda. Obviously, it is no substitute to actually
attending a conference and as such remains exclusionary, but it could be a
useful tool in a difficult situation that does not admit of easy solutions.

Finally, to address a particular point that have been raised:

I'm afraid I do not know about the specifics of laws aimed at known
activists. I will find out and let you know, Phoenix. This information will
then be on the website.

If my previous email was rushed and did not attend to the complexities of
the matter, I apologise. It has still not been possible to contact all the
members of the steering committee and I represent here, as program chair,
only my own thoughts. Again, anyone who wants to get in touch with us
outside of the listserv is most welcome to do so.

The steering committee will report back soon.

Best regards,

Feng



