ssia is, indeed, NOT safe for LGBT&#43; people. Therefore, visiting Russia =
requires a careful consideration.<br><br></p><p>Such consideration, however=
, must be based on a systemic approach and has to take into account as much=
 data as possible so an informed decision can be made. Statistics regarding=
 street attacks and censorship in media surely tell us how homophobic Russi=
an society and Russian government are, but they are of little help if our q=
uestion is how likely it is that an LGBT&#43; participant of an academic co=
nference gets into trouble. In that case we must consider the data regardin=
g the number of academic conferences attacked by the government or whoever =
else on the basis of anti-LGBT ideology. Now there is a very straightforwar=
d bifurcation: an event (academic or not) is either explicitly LGBT-themed =
or it is not. If it is, then problems might arise, because our governmental=
 or pro-governmental forces sometimes attack such events. But if it is not,=
 then it goes completely under the radar. Russian authorities don=E2=80=99t=
 care about academic life. Needless to say, they don=E2=80=99t have anybody=
 in charge of inspecting each and every academic conference for ideological=
 impurity. And it is exactly our case: this particular double-conference is=
n=E2=80=99t LGBT-themed. Moreover, its topic is nominally way outside of wh=
at our authorities consider to be politics. For our authorities, it is just=
 another academic event in a long chain of academic events which happen in =
our country all the time. There is no reason for them to pay any attention =
to this particular conference. We must take into account that Russia hosts =
many academic conferences in almost all academic fields each year (and we a=
lready hosted 2 international game studies conferences in particular). Now =
we must ask whether any non-LGBT-themed academic conference was ever attack=
ed in Russia on the basis of having LGBT people or LGBT-themed presentation=
s in them. Neither my colleagues, nor I can remember any such case, quick s=
earch also yields no results. To conclude: although nobody in a right mind =
will tell you that an LGBT person has nothing to be afraid of in Russia, th=
ere is also no reason to think that any reactionary forces will decide to t=
arget this particular academic conference on any basis, especially given th=
at this conference is in English.<br><br></p><p>Next, I=E2=80=99d like to a=
ddress a broader matter regarding organizing conferences in anti-democratic=
 countries in general. I believe there are LGBT&#43; scholars in all academ=
ic fields and I know that many academic fields within social sciences and h=
umanities have LGBT-related topics. If the democratic countries decide to w=
ithdraw all international conferences from anti-democratic countries for se=
curity reasons (until everyone becomes democratic), then I=E2=80=99m afraid=
 this enterprise is doomed. Again, if asked about whether or not we should =
have a Queer Game Studies conference in modern-day Russia I would do my bes=
t to discourage everyone from doing so. But if we stop having game studies =
conferences or any kind of academic conferences in general in Russia and si=
milarly repressive countries we will just further ghettoize their academic =
communities.</p><p><br></p><p>Just in case, I=E2=80=99m not here to tell an=
ybody &quot;how to academy&quot;; my point is, the longer this thread goes =
the more it sounds as if there were no academic conferences in Russia in an=
y field EVER and now we are about to have the very first one in history and=
 we have no idea how it may turn out. <span style=3D"text-decoration:underl=
ine">It is clearly not the case.</span> We started from whether or not it i=
s safe for LGBT&#43; people to attend this very particular game studies con=
ference, but after several posts I can see carpet-bombing statements regard=
ing whether or not we should organize academic events AS SUCH in countries =
like Russia =E2=80=93 or at least it sounds that way because it is not spec=
ified anymore whether it is about LGBT-themed conference or a conference in=
 general, whether it is a game studies conference or a conference in genera=
l. And I=E2=80=99d also like to make a remark about making a statement by e=
xcluding oppressive countries from potential conference hosts: the only peo=
ple how will hear such a statement are scholars who already support LGBT, b=
ecause oppressors themselves neither listen nor care.<br><br>This is a rush=
ed response so it might appear unbalanced, I apologize for that and hope th=
at it doesn't seem disrespectful towards anyone's position.</p></div><div><=
